---
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const posts = (await getCollection('posts'))
  .filter((p) => !p.data.draft)
  .sort((a, b) => b.data.date.getTime() - a.data.date.getTime())
  .slice(0, 4);
const fmt = new Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', { year: 'numeric', month: 'short', day: 'numeric' });
---

<Base title="Suryakant Kashyap — LLMs, retrieval, and the systems that make them work in production" description="Suryakant Kashyap is an AI engineer with a systems background. Writes about LLMs, retrieval-augmented generation, evals, and the production infrastructure underneath modern AI products.">
  <section class="mb-16">
    <p class="font-sans text-sm uppercase tracking-wider text-[color:var(--color-ink-faint)] mb-3">Suryakant Kashyap</p>
    <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-semibold leading-tight tracking-tight mb-5 text-balance">
      I build AI systems that survive production — and write down what I learn doing it.
    </h1>
    <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[color:var(--color-ink-muted)] mb-3">
      AI engineer with a systems background. I work on the parts of LLM products that don't make demo videos: retrieval pipelines, evals that catch regressions, prompt iteration that doesn't melt the bill, and the infrastructure that keeps it all running.
    </p>
    <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[color:var(--color-ink-muted)]">
      Currently a senior engineer at <a href="https://www.kloudfuse.com/">Kloudfuse</a>, where the AI work sits on top of a metrics and observability stack I've spent years building. The depth in the stack is what makes the AI layer on top honest. This site is the long-form record of both halves.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between mb-5">
      <h2 class="font-sans font-semibold text-base uppercase tracking-wider text-[color:var(--color-ink-faint)]">Recent posts</h2>
      <a href="/posts/" class="font-sans text-sm">All posts →</a>
    </div>
    <ul class="space-y-6">
      {posts.map((post) => (
        <li>
          <a href={`/posts/${post.id}/`} class="!no-underline group">
            <h3 class="font-sans font-medium text-lg !text-[color:var(--color-ink)] group-hover:!text-[color:var(--color-accent)] mb-1 leading-snug">
              {post.data.title}
            </h3>
            <p class="text-[color:var(--color-ink-muted)] leading-snug mb-1">{post.data.description}</p>
            <p class="font-sans text-xs text-[color:var(--color-ink-faint)]">
              {fmt.format(post.data.date)} · {post.data.tags.join(' · ')}
            </p>
          </a>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="font-sans font-semibold text-base uppercase tracking-wider text-[color:var(--color-ink-faint)] mb-5">What I work on</h2>
    <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[color:var(--color-ink-muted)] mb-3">
      <strong class="!text-[color:var(--color-ink)] font-medium">AI / ML.</strong> Retrieval-augmented generation, eval design, prompt iteration, and the operational ceiling — what an AI feature actually costs at scale, where it breaks, and how you stop it from regressing every time a model changes. I built <a href="/posts/aida-natural-language-to-promql/">AIDA</a> — a natural-language-to-PromQL prototype — in 2023, before "RAG" was the household term.
    </p>
    <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[color:var(--color-ink-muted)] mb-3">
      <strong class="!text-[color:var(--color-ink)] font-medium">Systems.</strong> I write the metrics query path for <strong class="!text-[color:var(--color-ink)] font-medium">Kloudfuse</strong> — a Prometheus-compatible API that fronts Apache Pinot. PromQL semantics, rollup planning, histogram correctness, query priority, rule evaluation. Years of this is what makes the AI half of the work credible.
    </p>
    <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[color:var(--color-ink-muted)]">
      The <a href="/about/">about page</a> connects the two halves; the <a href="/work/">work page</a> has the case studies.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
